00:34:36.639 --> 00:34:45.020
&gt;&gt;[INAUDIBLE SPEAKER]

00:34:45.020 --> 00:34:53.399
&gt;&gt;[INAUDIBLE QUESTION]

00:34:53.399 --> 00:35:09.310
DR. RON DEIBERT: Yep, sure. The question was
about Australia, and the

00:35:09.310 --> 00:35:14.720
proposals there for a national filtering system.
And we've been engaging in monitoring in Australia

00:35:14.720 --> 00:35:16.451
just like in a lot
of other countries.

00:35:16.451 --> 00:35:21.510
This is a proposal is being discussed as far
as I know, anyway.

00:35:21.510 --> 00:35:24.881
But it's emblematic of the type of discussion
that's happening in a lot

00:35:24.881 --> 00:35:29.900
of other advanced, industrialized countries.
I think the difference with Australia was

00:35:29.900 --> 00:35:34.550
a bit more extreme of a
proposal than what's happening say in Canada.

00:35:34.550 --> 00:35:38.830
In Canada, the model is for private companies
have entered into a

00:35:38.830 --> 00:35:42.630
voluntary arrangement.
It's not that a law has been imposed upon

00:35:42.630 --> 00:35:46.050
them.
Where they're blocking access to a list of

00:35:46.050 --> 00:35:50.500
sites containing images and
texts and so on of child abuse.

00:35:50.500 --> 00:35:56.810
Child pornography.
The list of information is provided by a kind

00:35:56.810 --> 00:36:01.100
of civic organization, a
monitoring organization, Cybertip.

00:36:01.100 --> 00:36:05.950
And I guess, you know, first of all, let me
say about this discussion

00:36:05.950 --> 00:36:08.930
as a whole, it's always a very difficult one
to enter into.

00:36:08.930 --> 00:36:13.300
Because right away it's -- it's one of those
areas of conversation

00:36:13.300 --> 00:36:17.610
where you hesitate to sound like a defender
of the content in question.

00:36:17.610 --> 00:36:20.190
Because I think, you know, this is one case
where certainly I believe

00:36:20.190 --> 00:36:26.511
this content is objectionable.
It's already illegal to circulate and produce

00:36:26.511 --> 00:36:28.140
in many countries.
And I think that's great.

00:36:28.140 --> 00:36:31.040
So the question is not about whether this
content should be circulating

00:36:31.040 --> 00:36:34.580
or not, at least in my mind.
It's about how to deal with it.

00:36:34.580 --> 00:36:38.060
And I think in the case of Canada, you have
a very bad solution.

00:36:38.060 --> 00:36:40.420
And the case of Australia is probably even
worse.

00:36:40.420 --> 00:36:45.770
In the case of Canada, private companies are
undertaking this mission

00:36:45.770 --> 00:36:50.220
with the help of this Cybertip.
Researchers can't examine the block list.

00:36:50.220 --> 00:36:52.880
We're not allowed to check whether there are
any errors.

00:36:52.880 --> 00:36:57.480
There's no government oversight.
There's no way for citizens who are concerned

00:36:57.480 --> 00:37:01.480
about whether their
content is included mistakenly in this category,

00:37:01.480 --> 00:37:05.020
is a problem.
So to me there are a lot of issues with this.

00:37:05.020 --> 00:37:08.369
Actually, Nart Villeneuve in the back of the
room here, did a chapter

00:37:08.369 --> 00:37:13.700
for Access Control on this topic.
And Nart, if you -- do you want to add anything

00:37:13.700 --> 00:37:14.700
to that?

00:37:14.700 --> 00:37:16.470
[PAUSE]

00:37:16.470 --> 00:37:24.610
&gt;&gt;Is this working?
Well, I think the main problem is the tension

00:37:24.610 --> 00:37:27.270
between filtering which
is sort of easy.

00:37:27.270 --> 00:37:34.000
And take down which is much more difficult.
So, what happens is there are organizations

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:51.930
all over the world that act
in this same way that Cybertip does, like

00:37:51.930 --> 00:38:01.720
the Internet Watch Foundation
in the UK.

00:38:01.720 --> 00:38:14.850
They accept tips from the public, and then
they check to make sure that

00:38:14.850 --> 00:38:18.240
those URLs --
at least I think they're URLs, and hopefully

00:38:18.240 --> 00:38:19.420
not domain names or IP addresses --
contain illegal content, give them to the

00:38:19.420 --> 00:38:20.420
ISPs.
The ISPs block them with whatever method they

00:38:20.420 --> 00:38:21.420
choose.
Then what happens is they don't circulate

00:38:21.420 --> 00:38:22.420
that information amongst
other tip agencies.

00:38:22.420 --> 00:38:26.820
So when Canadian authorities find bad sites
in the UK, we just block

00:38:26.820 --> 00:38:30.020
them.
We don't phone them up and say, "Hey, you

00:38:30.020 --> 00:38:31.020
have these bad sites over
there.

00:38:31.020 --> 00:38:33.200
Maybe you should do something about it."
So Canada actually blocks content that's hosted

00:38:33.200 --> 00:38:34.200
in the U.S., despite
the fact that we have two law enforcement

00:38:34.200 --> 00:38:35.200
 --
like joint law enforcement agencies that are

00:38:35.200 --> 00:38:36.200
targeting -- that are supposed to work on
the issue of images of child abuse online.

00:38:36.200 --> 00:38:37.200
And a network of operators like Cybertip,
they're supposed to exchange

00:38:37.200 --> 00:38:38.200
information.
So someone's dropping the ball somewhere.

00:38:38.200 --> 00:38:40.130
The result is that people block a minute amount
of content to prevent

00:38:40.130 --> 00:38:41.850
-- and they clearly state it's to prevent
 -- accidental access to

00:38:41.850 --> 00:38:43.780
images of child abuse.
So it has nothing to do with trying to get

00:38:43.780 --> 00:38:45.110
that content offline,
figuring out who's circulating that and posting

00:38:45.110 --> 00:38:53.010
that content.
It's just a very kind of -- we fill in the

00:38:53.010 --> 00:38:58.030
bullet point on the
presentation to say we're doing something

00:38:58.030 --> 00:39:00.530
about this issue kind of solution.

00:39:00.530 --> 00:39:01.980
DR. RON DEIBERT: Thanks, Nart.

00:39:01.980 --> 00:39:09.420
&gt;&gt;[INAUDIBLE QUESTION]

00:39:09.420 --> 00:39:30.241
DR. RON DEIBERT: Geez, that's a question for
all the Google engineers

00:39:30.241 --> 00:39:32.820
here.
I have no idea.

00:39:32.820 --> 00:39:39.360
Interesting, I suppose.
I mean to me the findings of the ONI's research

00:39:39.360 --> 00:39:42.370
in that area --
For those who didn't hear the question is

00:39:42.370 --> 00:39:45.460
about the blocking disproportionately of local
language content --

00:39:45.460 --> 00:39:50.110
could machine translation help?
And you know as I said I think it's a interesting

00:39:50.110 --> 00:39:53.991
question.
But -- for me the what we've done there I

00:39:53.991 --> 00:39:56.750
think is interesting to a
certain extent.

00:39:56.750 --> 00:40:01.320
To me, it's -- it's all of the other ways
in which controls are being

00:40:01.320 --> 00:40:04.420
exercised now that are becoming much more
important.

00:40:04.420 --> 00:40:09.580
And our research doesn't really get at.
And that's troubling to me and a few others.

00:40:09.580 --> 00:40:14.810
And we need to really refine the way we think
about doing what we do.

00:40:14.810 --> 00:40:17.960
Although, it's still interesting as a snapshot
that a lot of countries

00:40:17.960 --> 00:40:26.660
target local language content, sure.

00:40:26.660 --> 00:40:34.630
&gt;&gt;[INAUDIBLE QUESTION]

00:40:34.630 --> 00:40:49.080
DR. RON DEIBERT: Well, sure.
I mean, beginning in this country, there was

00:40:49.080 --> 00:40:52.340
 -- one of the most
interesting things about the Cyber Security

00:40:52.340 --> 00:40:58.010
Review was that the world's
worse-kept secret about information operations

00:40:58.010 --> 00:41:01.890
and computer network
attacks was being openly discussed for the

00:41:01.890 --> 00:41:04.730
first time.
So it's not that it wasn't going on before.

00:41:04.730 --> 00:41:08.760
It's now being legitimized.
I think that was a very important threshold

00:41:08.760 --> 00:41:11.760
that had been crossed.
Actually, I was among a group of people that

00:41:11.760 --> 00:41:15.980
commented on the cyber
security announcement that Obama made.

00:41:15.980 --> 00:41:19.500
And that was the one thing that struck -- one
of the things that struck

00:41:19.500 --> 00:41:24.619
me was this fact.
And once that happens, of course, it creates

00:41:24.619 --> 00:41:29.001
a typical spiral in
international relations where other countries

00:41:29.001 --> 00:41:31.171
feel compelled to follow
suit and so on.

00:41:31.171 --> 00:41:35.190
I think right now, you know, the reason that
the idea of cyber arms

00:41:35.190 --> 00:41:40.030
control is dismissed as so naive --
for one reason anyway, is because the momentum

00:41:40.030 --> 00:41:46.040
is so much in the other direction right now.
So many countries are seeing this as an area

00:41:46.040 --> 00:41:48.030
where they need to catch
up, first of all.

00:41:48.030 --> 00:41:51.130
And also an area that yields very valuable
information.

00:41:51.130 --> 00:41:54.460
As I said, most of our research now is in
this domain of targeted

00:41:54.460 --> 00:41:57.600
surveillance, targeted espionage, malware
and so on.

00:41:57.600 --> 00:42:01.470
And looking at the type of research that's
done by Greg Walton and Nart

00:42:01.470 --> 00:42:04.460
and the people who are working at the Citizen
Lab on this topic.

00:42:04.460 --> 00:42:08.500
It's remarkable to me how much you can gain
access to because there is

00:42:08.500 --> 00:42:13.240
such a insecure underbelly to the Internet.
All of these devices that are connected to

00:42:13.240 --> 00:42:18.020
it that are highly insecure
yet contain sensitive information that can

00:42:18.020 --> 00:42:21.590
be collected and used for
whatever purposes.

00:42:21.590 --> 00:42:25.900
I think is now such an attractive thing for
intelligence, for military

00:42:25.900 --> 00:42:28.790
that it's creating this dynamic of an arms
race.

00:42:28.790 --> 00:42:31.470
And I think it's affecting what we used to
call in the past Internet

00:42:31.470 --> 00:42:35.080
censorship, which we thought of at least I
did, well, this is something

00:42:35.080 --> 00:42:38.220
that governments do.
They program content into routers somewhere,

00:42:38.220 --> 00:42:39.540
and you're not able to
access it.

00:42:39.540 --> 00:42:43.850
Where this is -- there's a whole bigger fish
floating out there.

00:42:43.850 --> 00:42:48.450
A much bigger set of problems that we need
to put this in the context

00:42:48.450 --> 00:42:58.290
of -- including circumvention technologies,
I would say.

